rComments: Ehh... he's aight. I stopped paying attention because I didn't really understand him and thought it was all review, but got screwed over by integration. Not really stimulating at all, can't say much about him. Just do problems in DGDs and the textbook if you're having trouble.

very enthusiastic about the subject and teaching. each new topic would give a brief explanation of what we needed to know, then show us the formulas/theorems and sometimes derivations/proofs. then examples. he would then relate what ever he was teaching with what it would be USED for as engineers which showed he actually cared about teaching.

Great knowledge of the material and great at explaining it. He is a fair marker on the midterms. Three midterms, drop the worst one if your final exam mark is better than any of them. Applies the material learned in class to real-life applications which is intriguing. He is monotonous but the lectures tend to end early. Accessible out of class.

He explains things clearly and concisely, often finishing lectures a bit early. His voice is a bit monotonous. He assumes that you know calculus I, and the pace is super fast. His lecture notes are taken straight from the textbook and are more of a summary. He gives three midterms, and the first one is early on in January, so beware and prepare .
